* Standard debugging techniques should be used.
* Specific debugging procedures for project components will be added here.  Addressing file access timeouts is required. The consistent timeouts accessing project files require immediate investigation and resolution.  This includes investigating potential network issues, file permission problems, or resource constraints.
* Error during `pip install -r requirements.txt` needs debugging by SET.  See WORKFLOW & RELEASE RULES for details.  Solutions implemented include a modified requirements file (`requirements_py313.txt`), a setup script (`setup_py313.py`), and updated documentation in the README.md.  See PROJECT DOCUMENTATION & CONTEXT SYSTEM for details.
* To resolve "git is not recognized" error:  If Git is not installed, download from https://git-scm.com/downloads and ensure "add Git to your PATH" is selected during installation. Restart your terminal. If Git is already installed, locate the Git installation path (e.g., `C:\Program Files\Git\bin`), add it to the system PATH environment variable, and restart your terminal.  If the GitHub Pull Requests extension is installed, the issue is likely with the PATH configuration. Check the Git installation location (`C:\Program Files\Git\bin`, `C:\Program Files (x86)\Git\bin`, `C:\Users\[YourUsername]\AppData\Local\Programs\Git\bin`) and add the path to the bin directory to the system PATH environment variable. Restart Cursor after updating the PATH.  Alternatively, use the full path to Git in your commands or temporarily add Git to your session PATH in the terminal using `set PATH=%PATH%;C:\Program Files\Git\bin` (adjusting the path as needed).  Further troubleshooting steps for Git PATH issues include verifying Git installation location using `where.exe git` or directory searches, checking the current PATH variable with `echo $env:PATH`, temporarily adding Git to the PATH using PowerShell (`$env:PATH += ";C:\Program Files\Git\bin;C:\Program Files\Git\cmd"`), permanently adding Git to the user PATH using PowerShell (See detailed instructions in the new AI interactions), verifying VS Code/Cursor Git configuration, and using a script to install Git if needed.


